1160","1193":"1193","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","about 1216":"about 1216","1155":"1155",", Lincolnshire, , England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Gosberkirk, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Beaurepaire, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Rea  .","English: topographic name for someone living at a place where rye (Old English <i>ryge</i>) was grown, or perhaps an occupational name for someone who grew or sold it.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads so named, most of them from Old Norse <i>rjóthr</i> ‘clearing in a forest’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ryer","meanings":["English (Sussex and Kent): probably from   Rye   (see   Rea  ) + the suffix <i>-er</i>, and is thus synonymous with Middle English <i>atte Rye</i>, denoting someone who lived by a river or an island. This type of formation is common in Sussex and Kent.","Americanized form of German   Reier   ‘heron’ or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rajar</b> or <b>Rajer</b> (see   Rayer  )."]},{"name":"Romney","meanings":["English: habitational name from Romney (Kent), from an uncertain first element (perhaps an Old English personal name <i>Rūmen</i>) + Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’. Compare   Rye   2."]},{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Philip de Rye was born in 1196, in Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Robert de Rye, was 42 and his mother, Mrs Robert de Rye, was 37. He married Kinna of Gosberton in 1220, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1251, in Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1196–1251":"1196–1251","1178–Male":"1178–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1193–Male":"1193–Surnud","1202–1226":"1202–1226","1226–1260":"1226–1260","1216–1230":"1216–1230","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1196":"1196","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","about 1216":"umbes 1216","1155":"1155",", Lincolnshire, , England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gosberkirk, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beaurepaire, Lincolnsh